Hi [~sjones], What is meant by "cloud controller configured to use itself for name resolution" ? Does it mean that following property points to CLC?

{{system.dns.nameserveraddress}} 

[~spark] , I will raise separate customer escalation as this has been found at customer location as well. The problem is easily reproducible if we run {{dnsperf}} against the CLC like this

{code}
dnsperf -s <CLC IP ADDRESS> -l 1000 -c 10 -d <query file>
{code}

After this is finished UDP handler gets hung up and recover by itself after sometime (normally 10 minutes or so) but when it is hung up it is basically not usable but TCP handler is working just fine.

I have attached the query file and startup.log that contains the thread dumps if someone is interested to look at them. Please let me know if you have any questions.

Cheers!
Deependra

[~spark],

When using dnsperf, there is the -s option:

{code}
dnsperf -d queryfile -s 10.104.10.12 -n 1000
{code}

This option states the following:

{code}
-s the server to query (default: 127.0.0.1)
{code}

With regards to dig, the DNS server to query can be passed at the end by doing the following:

{code}
dig <dns name> @<CLC IP>
{code}

I may be mistaken here, but I don't think editing /etc/resolv.conf will be necessary if these options are used.

Verified that
{code}
dig compute.c-28.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com @10.111.1.63 +tcp
{code}
and
{code}
dig compute.c-28.autoqa.qa1.eucalyptus-systems.com @10.111.1.63 +notcp
{code}
works as expected
